## Problem

The database is in-memory EF Core. On cold start, only 12 knowledge base articles are seeded — zero tickets exist. When someone hits the Azure URL cold (e.g. from a LinkedIn link), they see an empty dashboard: `0` total tickets, `0.0%` resolution rate, blank charts. The app looks broken.

## Solution

After seeding the knowledge base in `Program.cs`, run the simulation pipeline to auto-generate ~25 demo tickets. This populates the dashboard with real classified/deflected data on first load.

In `Program.cs`, after the existing `SeedData.Initialize(context)` block (lines 17–22), add a startup seed that:

1. Checks if the database already has tickets (guard against re-seeding on hot reload)
2. If no tickets exist, resolves `PipelineService` from the DI container
3. Runs the same simulation logic that `SimulateEndpoints.RunSimulation` uses — loop through ~25 random sample tickets from `SimulateEndpoints.SampleTickets`, calling `pipeline.ProcessTicket()` for each
4. This requires making the `SampleTickets` array in `SimulateEndpoints.cs` accessible (it's currently `private static readonly`). Either:
   - Make it `internal static readonly` so `Program.cs` can reference it, OR
   - Extract it to a shared static class (e.g. `SampleTicketData`), OR
   - Inline a simpler version directly in the startup code

The simplest approach: make `SampleTickets` in `SimulateEndpoints.cs` `internal` instead of `private`, then in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
// Seed knowledge base on startup
using (var scope = app.Services.CreateScope())
{
    var context = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<TicketDbContext>();
    SeedData.Initialize(context);

    // Auto-populate dashboard with demo tickets
    if (!context.Tickets.Any())
    {
        var pipeline = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<PipelineService>();
        var random = new Random(42); // fixed seed for deterministic demo data
        for (var i = 0; i < 25; i++)
        {
            var template = SimulateEndpoints.SampleTickets[random.Next(SimulateEndpoints.SampleTickets.Length)];
            await pipeline.ProcessTicket(template.Title, template.Description, template.Source, context);
        }
    }
}
```

Note: This requires changing `Main` to `async Task Main` (or using `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`) since `ProcessTicket` is async. The `Program.cs` top-level statements may need adjustment.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] On app startup, ~25 demo tickets are automatically processed through the full pipeline (classify → match → resolve/escalate)
- [ ] Tickets and activity logs are persisted to the database before the app starts accepting requests
- [ ] `GET /api/metrics/overview` returns `totalTickets >= 25` on first cold request (no user interaction needed)
- [ ] `GET /dashboard` shows populated stat cards and charts on first load
- [ ] `GET /tickets` shows ticket cards on first load
- [ ] `GET /activity` shows activity log entries on first load
- [ ] Guard: if tickets already exist in DB, skip the auto-seed (idempotent)
- [ ] `dotnet build TicketDeflection.sln` succeeds with 0 errors
- [ ] `dotnet test TicketDeflection.sln` — no regressions (existing tests still pass)
- [ ] No `.github/workflows/` files modified

## Problem

When the user clicks "Run Demo" on the landing page (`/`), the simulation runs and displays raw JSON output in a `<pre>` tag. The user has to manually navigate to `/dashboard` to see the populated metrics. This breaks the demo flow — the payoff should be immediate.

## Solution

In `TicketDeflection/Pages/Index.cshtml`, update the `runDemo()` JavaScript function to redirect to `/dashboard` after the simulation completes successfully, instead of displaying raw JSON.

Current behavior (approximately lines 57–70 of Index.cshtml):
```javascript
async function runDemo() {
    // ... disable button, show loading ...
    const response = await fetch('/api/simulate?count=25', { method: 'POST' });
    const data = await response.json();
    resultsContent.textContent = JSON.stringify(data, null, 2);
    results.classList.remove('hidden');
    // ... re-enable button ...
}
```

New behavior:
```javascript
async function runDemo() {
    // ... disable button, show loading ...
    const response = await fetch('/api/simulate?count=25', { method: 'POST' });
    if (response.ok) {
        window.location.href = '/dashboard';
    } else {
        // Show error inline
        resultsContent.textContent = 'Simulation failed. Please try again.';
        results.classList.remove('hidden');
        // ... re-enable button ...
    }
}
```

User clicks "Run Demo" → simulation runs → browser navigates to `/dashboard` → user sees a fully populated dashboard with metrics, charts, ticket counts. Clean one-click demo loop.

## Dependencies

- Depends on #190 (auto-seed demo data on startup). With #190 shipped, the dashboard is already populated on cold start and this button becomes "generate more tickets" rather than a prerequisite. But the redirect still improves UX by closing the demo loop.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Clicking "Run Demo" on `/` triggers the simulation and redirects to `/dashboard` on success
- [ ] On error, an inline error message is shown (no redirect)
- [ ] The `/dashboard` page shows updated metrics reflecting the newly simulated tickets
- [ ] `dotnet build TicketDeflection.sln` succeeds with 0 errors
- [ ] No `.github/workflows/` files modified

